article.description: James Posey scored 15 of his season-high 26 points in the first quarter as the Rockets tied a season high with their fourth straight win, a 121-91 rout of the Bulls.
article.headline: Posey picks on Bulls as Rockets romp
article.linkText: Posey (26 points) picks on Bulls as Rockets romp
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Right from the outset, James Posey made the Chicago Bulls pay for leaving him open.
Posey

"It felt good to have the opportunity to take a bunch of open shots,'' Posey said after his season-high 26 points led the Houston Rockets to a 121-91 victory over Chicago on Friday night. It was the most lopsided loss of the season for the Bulls, while Houston matched its season high in points scored and margin of victory. "I was just trying to get easy baskets in transition, that's my game,'' Posey said. "On the defensive end we didn't let up. We tried to bury them.'' Posey scored 12 points in a 16-3 run to open the game and the Rockets were never threatened again. It was Houston's fourth consecutive victory, matching its longest winning streak of the season. Steve Francis had 23 points, followed by Glen Rice and Yao Ming 16 each and Cuttino Mobley with 13. "Posey came out and set the tone. He knocked the ball loose, made some shots and got the running game going,'' Houston coach Rudy Tomjanovich said. Chicago coach Bill Cartwright was disappointed with his team's play. "Out of our first group, the only guy that was ready to play was Jamal (Crawford),'' Cartwright complained. "Sometimes you can't throw it in the ocean and the other team is hot. This was one of those nights,'' Cartwright continued. "We've just got to get ourselves ready to play basketball.'' The Rockets led 52-25 with 3:03 left in the half and 55-33 at intermission, with Posey contributing 17 first-half points. Chicago pulled to 82-63 in the third period but trailed 89-65 going in the final quarter.

Game notes
Yao has connected on at least half of his field goals attempts in 15 of his last 21 games ... Chicago's 3-32 road record is the worst in the NBA.
